column11: u"Upgrades the operating system of the specified pool.  During an upgrade
column12: the Batch service upgrades each compute node in the pool. When a compute node is chosen for upgrade
column13: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column14: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column15: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column16: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column17: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column18: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column19: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column20: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."]

column16: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column17: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs

column20: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from

samples: [u"Upgrades the operating system of the specified pool.  During an upgrade
column11: the Batch service upgrades each compute node in the pool. When a compute node is chosen for upgrade
column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column15: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column18: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column19: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."

samples: [u'backup protection backup-now'
column11: u"Upgrades the operating system of the specified pool.  During an upgrade
column12: the Batch service upgrades each compute node in the pool. When a compute node is chosen for upgrade
column13: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column14: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column15: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column16: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column17: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column18: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column19: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column20: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."]

column13: u"Copies a blob asynchronously. This operation returns a copy operation  properties object
column14: including a copy ID you can use to check or abort the  copy operation. The Blob service copies blobs on a best-effort basis.  The source blob for a copy operation may be a block blob
column15: an append blob
column16: or a page blob. If the destination blob already exists
column17: it must be of the  same blob type as the source blob. Any existing destination blob will be  overwritten. The destination blob cannot be modified while a copy operation  is in progress.  When copying from a page blob
column18: the Blob service creates a destination page  blob of the source blob's length
column19: initially containing all zeroes. Then  the source page ranges are enumerated
column20: and non-empty ranges are copied.   For a block blob or an append blob
column21: the Blob service creates a committed  blob of zero length before returning from this operation. When copying  from a block blob
column22: all committed blocks and their block IDs are copied.  Uncommitted blocks are not copied. At the end of the copy operation
column23: the  destination blob will have the same committed block count as the source.  When copying from an append blob
column24: all committed blocks are copied. At the  end of the copy operation
column25: the destination blob will have the same committed  block count as the source.  For all blob types
column26: you can call get_blob_properties on the destination  blob to check the status of the copy operation. The final blob will be  committed when the copy completes."]

column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs

column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from

As computing the MD5 takes processing time and more requests will need to be done due to the reduced chunk size there may be some increase in latency.']

Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time

column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from

samples: [u"Upgrades the operating system of the specified pool.  During an upgrade
column11: the Batch service upgrades each compute node in the pool. When a compute node is chosen for upgrade
column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column15: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column18: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column19: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."]

column17: it must be of the  same blob type as the source blob. Any existing destination blob will be  overwritten. The destination blob cannot be modified while a copy operation  is in progress.  When copying from a page blob
column18: the Blob service creates a destination page  blob of the source blob's length
column19: initially containing all zeroes. Then  the source page ranges are enumerated
column20: and non-empty ranges are copied.   For a block blob or an append blob
column21: the Blob service creates a committed  blob of zero length before returning from this operation. When copying  from a block blob
column22: all committed blocks and their block IDs are copied.  Uncommitted blocks are not copied. At the end of the copy operation
column23: the  destination blob will have the same committed block count as the source.  When copying from an append blob
column24: all committed blocks are copied. At the  end of the copy operation
column25: the destination blob will have the same committed  block count as the source.  For all blob types
column26: you can call get_blob_properties on the destination  blob to check the status of the copy operation. The final blob will be  committed when the copy completes."]
